n_count":1,"individual_name":"Sue Kuestner","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Control Pickup","individual_id":"019d0f2d-5e53-7877-9cb9-5a121c3f4087","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Viktor","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Course Designer","individual_id":"019b7ac9-920b-7388-83fe-900fc64d5761","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Peter Golde","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Course Designer(s)","individual_id":"019b7ac9-920b-7388-83fe-900fc64d5761","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Peter Golde","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Epunch Coordinator","individual_id":"01913919-da03-757e-b829-aa2bdc684400","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Debbie Newell","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Meet Director","individual_id":"019d0a40-c419-799a-97ec-c9f1967b2d4c","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Bob Stratton","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Meet Director","individual_id":"019b815e-cce3-782c-b020-2b625672abe6","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Robert Stratton","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Registration","individual_id":"019b7adf-f250-735f-9fc9-46fd3e9119b1","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Marjorie Stratton","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Start","individual_id":"019b8129-1684-72d5-8a8c-dcebca886fb8","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Brian Colella","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Start","individual_id":"019b815e-cce2-77d7-a0ca-1fa877e27dcf","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Valerie Enger","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null},{"role_name":"Start","individual_id":"019b7ac9-920b-7530-b85a-103e52302ff8","citation_count":1,"individual_name":"Will Enger","volunteer_hours":null,"volunteer_points":null}],"organizing_club_id":"01912f3e-e3e1-7e8e-b3c6-32387a8b4990","result_source_brief":"CascadeOC Website: https://cascadeoc.org/result/ultimate-orienteer-5-classic-fishtrap-lake/","organizing_club_name":"Cascade Orienteering Club","cumulative_event_comments":"Ultimate Orienteer #4 – Classic – Fishtrap Lake\nMany thanks to all the volunteers who helped out!\nCheck out 2-day totals\n\nPart of the Ultimate Orienteer Series, COC’s variety pack of orienteering events.\nDay 2 of a 2-day event at Fishtrap Lake. We’re going old-school! While each day will count separately for Ultimate Orienteer standings, we’ll also add the two days together for 2-day results.\nMake it an orienteering weekend and do Saturday’s event, also at Fishtrap.\nOut of Bounds areas\nMost of the area we’re using belongs to the Bureau of Land Management. They have identified several sensitive areas which are out of bounds for our competition. These areas are clearly marked on the map with vertical purple lines. The courses have been designed to avoid them, so make sure your route choice does not include travel through ANY out of bounds areas!\nWater\nGreen O is a large needle-leaved tree, green X is a large deciduous tree, and a green dot is a small tree or large bush. All three use the “tree” control description symbol.\nContours and cliffs are mapped very accurately and should be your primary means of navigation. Pay attention to the gaps between the cliffs, they can be quite important. If there is a visible gap, even a tiny one, then you should be able to get up or down, but solid cliffs are almost always too high to climb or descend. Check your control descriptions carefully; some controls are on the top of cliffs, while others are at the base.\nThe small trails have faded considerably and may be quite hard to follow, if not invisible (especially those with the intermittent double-dash symbol). I did not have time to recheck all the trails. It is extremely easy to run across one of the small trails without seeing it, or to not see a junction. Beware!\nThe water level is very high right now, much higher than is mapped. Anywhere you see the marsh symbol will be a significant pond, generally larger than the mapped marsh. Many depressions or low areas without mapped water have also become ponds of varying depths. If there is not an uncrossable boundary line, you are free to cross any water, and it will often be necessary. It will depend on route choice, but Long Advanced will need to wade knee to thigh deep for sure. Short Advanced will probably need to wade shin deep, and Intermediate will get at least ankle deep but possibly deeper. Beginner will be the only course where your shoes will remain dry.\nAll courses (even beginner) will cross barbed wire fences. Sliding under on your back is usually the easiest way through. Be careful, and please don’t damage them.\n\nPart of the Ultimate Orienteer Series, COC’s variety pack of orienteering events.\nDay 2 of a 2-day event at Fishtrap Lake. We’re going old-school! While each day will count separately for Ultimate Orienteer standings, we’ll also add the two days together for 2-day results.\nMake it an orienteering weekend and do Saturday’s event, also at Fishtrap.\nMost of the area we’re using belongs to the Bureau of Land Management. They have identified several sensitive areas which are out of bounds for our competition. These areas are clearly marked on the map with vertical purple lines. The courses have been designed to avoid them, so make sure your route choice does not include travel through ANY out of bounds areas!\nThere will be NO water on the courses, so plan to take your own. Fishtrap can get hot, even in May, so be prepared!\nThere will be water at the finish (you’ll pass this on the way to the start). Help us reduce waste by bringing your own bottle or cup.\nGreen O is a large needle-leaved tree, green X is a large deciduous tree, and a green dot is a small tree or large bush. All three use the “tree” control description symbol.\nContours and cliffs are mapped very accurately and should be your primary means of navigation. Pay attention to the gaps between the cliffs, they can be quite important. If there is a visible gap, even a tiny one, then you should be able to get up or down, but solid cliffs are almost always too high to climb or descend. Check your control descriptions carefully; some controls are on the top of cliffs, while others are at the base.\nThe small trails have faded considerably and may be quite hard to follow, if not invisible (especially those with the intermittent double-dash symbol). I did not have time to recheck all the trails. It is extremely easy to run across one of the small trails without seeing it, or to not see a junction. Beware!\nThe water level is very high right now, much higher than is mapped. Anywhere you see the marsh symbol will be a significant pond, generally larger than the mapped marsh. Many depressions or low areas without mapped water have also become ponds of varying depths. If there is not an uncrossable boundary line, you are free to cross any water, and it will often be necessary. It will depend on route choice, but Long Advanced will need to wade knee to thigh deep for sure. Short Advanced will probably need to wade shin deep, and Intermediate will get at least ankle deep but possibly deeper. Beginner will be the only course where your shoes will remain dry.\nAll courses (even beginner) will cross barbed wire fences. Sliding under on your back is usually the easiest way through. Be careful, and please don’t damage them.\n\nMany thanks to all the volunteers who helped out!\nResult status codes: msp = missing punch; dnf = did not finish; nc = not competing; dq = disqualified; ovt = overtime; dns = did not start.\nSource note: a starred time indicates course completion status was not reported and may be valid, msp, or dnf."}
